## Database Schema Rules

### Schema Compliance

- All database operations must respect the schema structure defined above
- Column types and constraints must match exactly as specified
- Use proper data types: CHAR(36) for UUIDs, VARCHAR for variable strings, INT for integers, JSON for structured data
- Respect NOT NULL constraints and default values

### Primary Keys

- All tables have primary keys (PK) as specified
- Use UUID (CHAR(36)) for most primary keys except ContentParameterAndMetadata and ContentParameterHistory (BIGINT AUTO_RANDOM)
- Composite primary keys use multiple columns (e.g., WorkflowParameter: workflowId, spaceId, name)

### Foreign Key Relationships

- Only DocumentActivityUsers.activityId has an explicit FK constraint with CASCADE DELETE
- All other relationships are logical - enforce referential integrity in application code
- When deleting records, manually handle cascading deletes for logical relationships

### Index Usage

- Use indexes for common query patterns (contentId lookups, workflowId lookups, date ordering)
- Respect unique constraints on indexes (workflowId+label, contentId+name, activityId+userId)
- Use composite indexes for multi-column queries (scope+containerId, contentId+date+orderSequence)

### JSON Columns

- Workflow.markup: Full workflow definition JSON
- WorkflowVersion.markup: Workflow markup at specific version
- DocumentActivity.payload: Activity-specific data JSON
- DocumentActivity.state: State snapshot JSON
- Use JSON extraction operators (`->>`) for generated columns (name, excludedLabels, stateName, etc.)

### Generated Columns

- Workflow.name: Extracted from `markup ->> '$.name'`
- Workflow.excludedLabels: From `markup.excludedLabels`
- DocumentActivity.stateName: From `state ->> '$.name'`
- DocumentActivity.stateColor: From `state ->> '$.colour'`
- DocumentActivity.stateFinal: From `state ->> '$.final'`
- DocumentActivity.contentVersion: From `state ->> '$.contentVersion'`

### Optimistic Locking

- ContentState.version: Increment on updates to prevent concurrent modification conflicts
- ContentParameterAndMetadata.version: Version for locking
- ContentApprovalDecision.version: Content version at decision
- WorkflowParameter.version: Version for locking
- Always check version before updates and increment on successful updates

### Data Types and Constraints

- Use SET type for multi-value enums (scope: 'global', 'space')
- Use ENUM type for single-value enums (contentType: 'page', 'blogpost')
- Use DATETIME for timestamps (UTC timezone)
- Use TINYINT(1) for boolean flags (enabled, visible, final)
- Use INT for version numbers and counts
- Use VARCHAR with appropriate length limits for strings
- Use TEXT for variable-length strings without length limit

### Migration Considerations

- When migrating data, respect all column types and constraints
- Handle NULL values appropriately (some columns allow NULL, others don't)
- Preserve relationships even though most are not enforced by FK constraints
- Maintain referential integrity in application code during migrations

### Query Patterns

- Always use indexes for WHERE clauses on indexed columns
- Use composite indexes for multi-column WHERE clauses
- Order by indexed columns (date DESC, orderSequence DESC) for DocumentActivity queries
- Use UNIQUE constraints to prevent duplicate entries (workflowId+label, contentId+name)

### Content State Relationships

- ContentState is the central table for content workflow state
- All content-related tables reference ContentState.contentId logically
- When querying content state, join with related tables using contentId
- Maintain consistency between ContentState and related tables (ContentApproval, Messages, DocumentActivity, etc.)

### Workflow Relationships

- Workflow is the central table for workflow definitions
- WorkflowLink, WorkflowLabel, WorkflowVersion, WorkflowParameter reference Workflow.id logically
- When querying workflows, join with related tables using workflowId
- Maintain consistency between Workflow and related tables
